```
public static void QuickSort(int[] array)
{
    // If the array has only one element, return it (since it's already sorted)
    if (array.Length == 1)
    {
        return;
    }

    // Choose a pivot element from the array
    int pivot = array[0];

    // Partition the array into two subarrays
    int leftIndex = 1;
    int rightIndex = array.Length - 1;
    while (leftIndex < rightIndex)
    {
        while (leftIndex < rightIndex && array[leftIndex] <= pivot)
        {
            leftIndex++;
        }
        while (rightIndex > leftIndex && array[rightIndex] > pivot)
        {
            rightIndex--;
        }
        if (leftIndex < rightIndex)
        {
            int temp = array[leftIndex];
            array[leftIndex] = array[rightIndex];
            array[rightIndex] = temp;
        }
    }

    // Recursively sort the left and right subarrays
    QuickSort(array, 0, leftIndex - 1);
    QuickSort(array, rightIndex + 1, array.Length - 1);
}
```
This implementation uses the "divide and conquer" strategy to sort the array. It chooses a pivot element from the array, partitions the array into two subarrays based on the pivot, and then recursively sorts the left and right subarrays.

To use this method, you can call it like this:
```
int[] array = { 10, 80, 30, 90, 40, 50, 70 };
QuickSort(array);
```
This will sort the array in ascending order and produce the result [10, 30, 40, 50, 70, 80, 90].

