Here are the basic operations that can be performed on a stack:

1. Push: Add an item to the top of the stack.
2. Pop: Remove the item from the top of the stack.
3. Peek: Look at the item at the top of the stack without removing it.

A queue, on the other hand, is a data structure that follows the First In, First Out (FIFO) principle, meaning that the first item added to the queue is the first one to be removed. A queue can be thought of as a line of people waiting in line, where people are added to the end of the line and removed from the front of the line.

Here are the basic operations that can be performed on a queue:

1. Enqueue: Add an item to the end of the queue.
2. Dequeue: Remove the item from the front of the queue.
3. Peek: Look at the item at the front of the queue without removing it.

